Question 1 : Define Data Transformation in ETL and explain why it is important.

Answere 1  : Data Transformation is the process of converting and cleaning data into a useful format during ETL.
             It removes errors, duplicates, and inconsistencies from data.
             It helps integrate data from different sources into a common format.
             This improves data quality and supports accurate reporting and decision-making.

Question 2 : List any four common activities involved in Data Cleaning.

Answere 2  : Removing duplicate records.
             Handling missing values.
             Correcting incorrect or invalid data.
             Standardizing data formats (e.g., date formats). 

Question 3 : What is the difference between Normalization and Standardization?

Answere 3  : Normalization: Scales data to a fixed range, usually 0 to 1.
            Standardization: Transforms data to have a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1.
            Normalization is useful when data has different scales.
            Standardization is useful when data follows a normal distribution.

Question 4 : A dataset has missing values in the “Age” column. Suggest two techniques to handle this and
             explain when they should be used.

Answere 4  : Remove missing records – Use when only a few rows have missing Age values and deleting them will not affect the dataset significantly.
             Replace with the mean/median age – Use when many values are missing and you want to keep all records in the dataset.
             Mean is suitable for normally distributed data.
             Median is better when the data contains outliers.

